def sns_barplot(x,y, tname, xrotation):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))

    splot=sns.barplot(x=x,y=y)

    for p in splot.patches:
        splot.annotate(format(p.get_height(), '.1f'), 
                       (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), 
                       ha = 'center', va = 'center', 
                       xytext = (0, 9), 
                       textcoords = 'offset points')

    splot.set_xticklabels(rotation=xrotation,labels=x)
    plt.title(tname)
    plt.show()

2) Sns_countplot()¶

In [16]:
def sns_countplot(x, hue, data, tname, xrotation):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    splot = sns.countplot(x=x, hue=hue, data=data)
    
    plt.xticks(None, None, rotation ='30')
    plt.title(tname)
    for p in splot.patches:
        splot.annotate('{:.1f}'.format(p.get_height()),(p.get_x()+0.1, p.get_height()+50))
    plt.show()

4) Contingency table and Chi square test functions:¶

In [17]:
# contingency table
def c_table(x, t):
    ct = pd.crosstab(df[x]\
                  .sample(frac=0.002, replace=True, random_state=1)\
                  ,df[t]\
                  .sample(frac=0.002, replace=True, random_state=1),margins = False) 
    return ct

def chi_test(c_t):
    stat, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(c_t)
    print('dof=%d' % dof)
    print('p_value', p)
    print(expected)

    # interpret test-statistic:
    prob = 0.95
    critical = chi2.ppf(prob, dof)

    print('probability=%.3f, critical=%.3f, stat=%.3f' % (prob, critical, stat))

    if abs(stat) >= critical:
        print('Dependent (reject H0)')
    else:
        print('Independent (fail to reject H0)')

Model Observations:
  1. While accuracy is a good starting point, looking at the F1 score or precison and recall is a more realistic approach to detecting if our classifier is performing well or not.
  2. For our dataset, as we do not have many class 0 (>50K) samples we see that the f1 score for outout label 1 i.e. >50K is only 61%, this shows that balancing the target column is important.
  3. ROC and AUC curves also are better means of determining the model performance. More the AUC score, better the model.

Performing K-fold cross validation to see if our accuracy imporves further more:¶

In [ ]:
# Lets check for odd numbers first to make it time efficient to find the K for KNN
neighbors = list(range(1, 30,2)) 

# Making an empty list to store the cross validation scores
cv_scores = []

# perform 10-fold cross validation
for k in neighbors:
    knn_cv = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    scores = cross_val_score(knn_cv, X_train,y_train, cv=5, scoring='accuracy') 
    cv_scores.append(scores.mean())

8. Improving the dataset issues:
  1. We noticed that the dataset is highly imbalanced, this may be solved by either oversampling or SMOTE to try to balance the number of samples for both the class labels.
  2. The number of categories in the categorical columns need to preprocessed before giving input to the model, this is evident from the native country column as if we do not process it then the model has almost 95 columns which adds a lot of computational time and is unecc for this dataset.
  3. The dataset is highly biased, even if we try to sample the data and level the dataset I feel for this dataset, it would be systhetically editting the dataset which would not help us. But, just by data preprocessing we got ~85% accuracy so I think if we use Random Forrest classifier we might be able to boost the model accuracy a bit.
  4. The Cross Validated model gives the most realistic model accuracy though we notice that for a vanilla knn model at k=29 we have higher accuracy. This shows that even if we have less accuracy having a more model which generalizes well is more imp. The predicted_y on test dataset is done for Knn where K=29.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is
    
    > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb
    
    which will convert mynotebook.ipynb to the default format (probably HTML).
    
    You can specify the export format with `--to`.
    Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides'].
    
    > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb
    
    Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
    'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic' and 'full'. You
    can specify the flavor of the format used.
    
    > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template basic mynotebook.ipynb
    
    You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file
    
    > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout
    
    PDF is generated via latex
    
    > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf
    
    You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow
    
    > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve
    
    Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of 
    different ways:
    
    > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
    > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb
    
    or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::
    
        c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]
    
    > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py
